{"id":408,"date":"2015-05-21T14:38:25","date_gmt":"2015-05-21T13:38:25","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.edlab.org.uk\/?p=408"},"modified":"2016-12-06T12:32:16","modified_gmt":"2016-12-06T12:32:16","slug":"mashing-up-music-coding-and-physical-computing","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/mashing-up-music-coding-and-physical-computing\/","title":{"rendered":"EdLab Spark: Mashing up Music, Coding and Physical Computing"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>The days of Computing and ICT as a subject where students are trapped behind computer screens are gone. There are now many ways to teach computational thinking and coding concepts. One of these ways is through creating music.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-881\" src=\"http:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021-800x533.jpg\" alt=\"sonic_pi_pgce_image021\" width=\"800\" height=\"533\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021-800x533.jpg 800w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021-300x200.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021-480x320.jpg 480w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/01\/sonic_pi_pgce_image021.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>The project involves Hive Manchester,\u00a0students of the Faculty of Education and the music educational project <a href=\"http:\/\/noisytoys.org\">Noisy Toys<\/a>. We will work together to create different creative educational experiences involving music and technology.<\/p>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p>Partner Name: Noisy Toys &#8211; http:\/\/noisytoys.org<br \/>\nSupervising Tutor: Mick Chesterman<br \/>\nKeywords: Acoustic Ecology, Electronics, Accessible computing teaching<\/p>\n<p>Steve Summers from Noisy Toys has set us this challenge. Don&#8217;t worry if this seems too technical. You will have guidance to be able to work on this challenge.<\/p>\n<blockquote><p>We want to take\u00a0standard Noisy Toys analogue and acoustic equipment to the next level by introducing a system for programming musical structure and sequences.\u00a0 A device such as a Raspberry Pi can easily be programmed to switch external circuits on and off, as well as produce varying voltages. This would be an ideal way to bring together some of the built-from-junk instruments and create a more orchestrated musical result that could combine coded trigger and voltage messages to play the instruments, mixed in with digitally produced sounds from Sonic Pi or and live playing of instruments. We are very interested in exploring this combination of Noisy Toys, code music and controller\u00a0technology further, and believe that it has great\u00a0potential.<\/p>\n<p>We want you to\u00a0help us to take this work into the classrooms in easy to follow steps.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p><\/blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The days of Computing and ICT as a subject where students are trapped behind computer screens are gone. There are now many ways to teach computational thinking and coding concepts. One of these ways is through creating music. The project involves Hive Manchester,\u00a0students of the Faculty of Education and the music educational project Noisy Toys. [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":29,"featured_media":420,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[128,129,1],"tags":[167,166,74,76,77,156,55,75,73],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v15.6.2 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<meta name=\"robots\" con